#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:9981
msgid "Logging &amp; Monitoring Authoritative Server performance"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:9983
msgid ""
"In a production environment, you will want to be able to monitor PDNS "
"performance. For this purpose, currently two methods are available, the "
"webserver and the init.d <command>dump</command>, <command>show</command> "
"and <command>mrtg</command>, commands. Furthermore, PDNS can perform a "
"configurable amount of operational logging. This chapter also explains how "
"to configure syslog for best results."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:9989
msgid "Webserver"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para><variablelist><varlistentry><term>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10002
msgid "webserver"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para><variablelist><varlistentry><listitem><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10005
msgid "If set to anything but 'no', a webserver is launched."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para><variablelist><varlistentry><term>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10010
msgid "webserver-address"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para><variablelist><varlistentry><listitem><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10013
msgid ""
"Address to bind the webserver to. Defaults to 127.0.0.1, which implies that "
"only the local computer is able to connect to the nameserver! To allow "
"remote hosts to connect, change to 0.0.0.0 or the physical IP address of "
"your nameserver."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para><variablelist><varlistentry><term>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10020
msgid "webserver-password"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para><variablelist><varlistentry><listitem><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10023
msgid ""
"If set, viewers will have to enter this plaintext password in order to gain "
"access to the statistics."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para><variablelist><varlistentry><term>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10028
msgid "webserver-port"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para><variablelist><varlistentry><listitem><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10031
msgid "Port to bind the webserver to. Defaults to 8081."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:9991
msgid ""
"To launch the internal webserver, add a <command>webserver</command> "
"statement to the pdns.conf. This will instruct the PDNS daemon to start a "
"webserver on localhost at port 8081, without password protection.  Only "
"local users (on the same host) will be able to access the webserver by "
"default.  The webserver \tlists a lot of information about the PDNS process, "
"including frequent queries, frequently failing queries, lists of remote "
"hosts sending queries, hosts sending corrupt queries etc. The webserver does "
"not allow remote management of the daemon.  The following nameserver related "
"configuration items are available: <placeholder type=\"variablelist\" "
"id=\"0\"/>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10039
msgid "Via init.d commands"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10041
msgid ""
"As mentioned before, the init.d commands <command>dump</command>, "
"<command>show</command> and <command>mrtg</command> fetch data from a "
"running PDNS process. Especially <command>mrtg</command> is powerful - it "
"outputs data in a format that is ready for processing by the MRTG graphing "
"tool."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10046
msgid ""
"MRTG can make insightful graphics on the performance of your nameserver, "
"enabling the operator to easily spot trends.  MRTG can be found on <ulink "
"url=\"http://people.ee.ethz.ch/~oetiker/webtools/mrtg/mrtg.html\"> "
"http://people.ee.ethz.ch/~oetiker/webtools/mrtg/mrtg.html </ulink>"
