#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10140
msgid "Operational logging using syslog"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10141
msgid "(<command>logging-facility</command> is available from 1.99.10 and onwards)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10143
msgid ""
"This chapter assumes familiarity with syslog, the unix logging device. PDNS "
"logs messages with different levels. The more urgent the message, the lower "
"the 'priority'. By default, PDNS will only log messages with an urgency of 3 "
"or lower, but this can be changed using the <command>loglevel</command> "
"setting in the configuration file. Setting it to 0 will eliminate all "
"logging, 9 will log everything."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10149
msgid ""
"By default, logging is performed under the 'DAEMON' facility which is shared "
"with lots of other programs. If you regard nameserving as important, you may "
"want to have it under a dedicated facility so PDNS can log to its own files, "
"and not clutter generic files."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10153
msgid ""
"For this purpose, syslog knows about 'local' facilities, numbered from "
"LOCAL0 to LOCAL7. To move PDNS logging to LOCAL0, add "
"<command>logging-facility=0</command> to your configuration."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10157
msgid ""
"Furthermore, you may want to have separate files for the differing "
"priorities - preventing lower priority messages from obscuring important "
"ones."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para><programlisting>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10163
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"local0.info                       -/var/log/pdns.info\n"
"local0.warn                       -/var/log/pdns.warn\n"
"local0.err                        /var/log/pdns.err\n"
"\t"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10161
msgid ""
"A sample syslog.conf might be: <placeholder type=\"programlisting\" "
"id=\"0\"/>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10169
msgid ""
"Where local0.err would store the really important messages. For performance "
"and disk space reasons, it is advised to audit your syslog.conf for "
"statements also logging PDNS activities. Many syslog.confs have a '*.*' "
"statement to /var/log/syslog, which you may want to remove."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10174
msgid ""
"For performance reasons, be especially certain that no large amounts of "
"synchronous logging take place. Under Linux, this is indicated by file names "
"not starting with a '-' - indicating a synchronous log, which hurts "
"performance."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10178
msgid ""
"Be aware that syslog by default logs messages at the configured priority and "
"higher! To log only info messages, use <command>local0.=info</command>."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10183
msgid "Security settings &amp; considerations"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10184
msgid "Settings"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10185
msgid ""
"PDNS has several options to easily allow it to run more securely. Most "
"notable are the <command>chroot</command>, <command>setuid</command> and "
"<command>setgid</command> options which can be specified."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10188
msgid ""
"For additional information on PowerDNS security, PowerDNS security incidents "
"and PowerDNS security policy, see <xref linkend=\"security-policy\"/>."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><sect2><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10190
msgid "Running as a less privileged identity"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><sect2><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10192
msgid ""
"By specifying <command>setuid</command> and <command>setgid</command>, PDNS "
"changes to this identity shortly after binding to the privileged DNS "
"ports. These options are highly recommended. It is suggested that a separate "
"identity is created for PDNS as the user 'nobody' is in fact quite powerful "
"on most systems."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><sect2><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10198
msgid ""
"Both these parameters can be specified either numerically or as real names.  "
"You should set these parameters immediately if they are not set!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><sect2><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10202
msgid "Jailing the process in a chroot"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><sect2><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10204
msgid ""
"The <command>chroot</command> option secures PDNS to its own directory so "
"that even if it should become compromised and under control of external "
"influences, it will have a hard time affecting the rest of the system."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><sect2><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10208
msgid ""
"Even though this will hamper hackers a lot, chroot jails have been known to "
"be broken."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><sect2><para><warning><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10213
msgid ""
"When chrooting PDNS, take care that backends will be able to get to their "
"files. Many databases need access to a UNIX domain socket which should live "
"within the chroot. It is often possible to hardlink such a socket into the "
"chroot dir."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><sect2><para><warning><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10217
msgid ""
"When running with master or slave support, be aware that many operating "
"systems need access to specific libraries (often "
"<filename>/lib/libnss*</filename>) in order to support resolution of domain "
"names! You can also hardlink these."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><sect2><para><warning><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10221
msgid ""
"In addition, make sure that <filename>/dev/log</filename> is available from "
"within the chroot. Logging will silently fail over time otherwise (on "
"logrotate)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><sect2><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10226
msgid ""
"The default PDNS configuration is best chrooted to <filename>./</filename>, "
"which boils down to the configured location of the controlsocket."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><sect2><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10229
msgid ""
"This is achieved by adding the following to pdns.conf: "
"<command>chroot=./</command>, and restarting PDNS."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10233
msgid "Considerations"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10235
msgid ""
"In general, make sure that the PDNS process is unable to execute commands on "
"your backend database.  Most database backends will only need SELECT "
"privilege. Take care to not connect to your database as the 'root' or 'sa' "
"user, and configure the chosen user to have very slight privileges."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10240
msgid ""
"Databases empathically do not need to run on the same machine that runs "
"PDNS! In fact, in benchmarks it has been discovered that having a separate "
"database machine actually improves performance."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10244
msgid "Separation will enhance your database security highly. Recommended."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10249
msgid "Virtual hosting"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10251
msgid ""
"It may be advantageous to run multiple separate PDNS installations on a "
"single host, for example to make sure that different customers cannot affect "
"each others zones. PDNS fully supports running multiple instances on one "
"host."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10255
msgid ""
"To generate additional PDNS instances, copy the init.d script "
"<filename>pdns</filename> to <filename>pdns-name</filename>, where "
"<filename>name</filename> is the name of your virtual configuration. Must "
"not contain a - as this will confuse the script."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10260
msgid ""
"When you launch PDNS via this renamed script, it will seek configuration "
"instructions not in <filename>pdns.conf</filename> but in "
"<filename>pdns-name.conf</filename>, allowing for separate specification of "
"parameters."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10264
msgid ""
"Be aware however that the init.d <command>force-stop</command> will kill all "
"PDNS instances!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10268
msgid "Authoritative Server Performance"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10269
msgid "General advice"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10271
msgid ""
"In general, best performance is achieved on recent Linux 2.6 kernels and "
"using MySQL, although many of the largest PowerDNS installations are based "
"on PostgreSQL. FreeBSD appears to achieve lower packet rates both for the "
"PowerDNS recursor as for the authoritative nameserver, this is still being "
"investigated. No comparative measurements have been done for Solaris "
"installations."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10276
msgid "On Linux, make sure to read <xref linkend=\"nptl\"/>."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10279
msgid ""
"Database servers can require configuration to achieve decent performance. It "
"is especially worth noting that several vendors ship PostgreSQL with a slow "
"default configuration."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10284
msgid "Native Posix Thread Library vs LinuxThreads"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10286
msgid ""
"To get the best performance under Linux, especially on SMP systems, the use "
"of NPTL is advised. The difference in performance can be over a factor of "
"ten in some circumstances."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10291
msgid ""
"NPTL is the default library on modern Linux distributions, so there is "
"generally not a problem, except if you use a statically compiled version "
"that, for portability reasons, defaults to LinuxThreads. This includes all "
".deb and .rpm files provided by us up to and including 2.9.18."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10298
msgid ""
"When running a PowerDNS-provided static binary of 2.9.18 or lower, it may "
"make sense to recompile, or to upgrade to a newer version, if "
"available. When recompiling, be sure to use a supported compiler, like g++ "
"&gt;3.2. You might also consider moving to a distribution supplied version."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10305
msgid ""
"A good indication that your installation might benefit from such an upgrade "
"is to watch the 'cs' count in the output of vmstat 1. If this is very high "
"(&gt; 10000), you are suffering from a LinuxThreads performance problem "
"called 'overspin'."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10311
msgid ""
"Thanks are due to L. Bunt Jackson who noted the static compilation problem "
"in an article in Dr. Dobb's Journal."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10316
msgid "Performance related settings"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10318
msgid ""
"Different backends will have different characteristics - some will want to "
"have more parallel instances than others. In general, if your backend is "
"latency bound, like most relational databases are, it pays to open more "
"backends."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10323
msgid ""
"This is done with the <command>distributor-threads</command> setting. Of "
"special importance is the choice between 1 or more backends. In case of only "
"1 thread, PDNS reverts to unthreaded operation which may be a lot faster, "
"depending on your operating system and architecture."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10328
msgid ""
"Another very important setting <command>cache-ttl</command>. PDNS caches "
"entire packets it sends out so as to save the time to query backends to "
"assemble all data. The default setting of 20 seconds may be low for high "
"traffic sites, a value of 60 seconds rarely leads to problems."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10333
msgid ""
"Some PDNS operators set cache-ttl to many hours or even days, and use "
"<command>pdns_control purge</command> to selectively or globally notify PDNS "
"of changes made in the backend. Also look at the Query Cache described in "
"this chapter. It may materially improve your performance."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10338
msgid ""
"To determine if PDNS is unable to keep up with packets, determine the value "
"of the <command>qsize-q</command> variable.  This represents the number of "
"packets waiting for database attention. During normal operations the queue "
"should be small."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10343
msgid ""
"Much the same holds for the <command>wildcards</command> setting. On by "
"default, each non-existent query will lead to a number of additional "
"wildcard queries. If it is known that the backends do not contain wildcard "
"records, performance can be improved by adding "
"<command>wildcards=no</command> to <filename>pdns.conf</filename>."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10348
msgid ""
"Logging truly kills performance as answering a question from the cache is an "
"order of magnitude less work than logging a line about it. Busy sites will "
"prefer to turn <command>log-dns-details</command> and "
"<command>log-failed-updates</command> off."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><sect2><para><variablelist><varlistentry><term>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10352 docs/pdns.xml:12463
msgid "Packet Cache"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><sect2><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10354
msgid ""
"PDNS by default uses the 'Packet Cache' to recognise identical questions and "
"supply them with identical answers, without any further processing. The "
"default time to live is 10 seconds. It has been observed that the utility of "
"the packet cache increases with the load on your nameserver."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><sect2><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10359
msgid ""
"Not all backends may benefit from the packetcache. If your backend is memory "
"based and does not lead to context switches, the packetcache may actually "
"hurt performance."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><sect2><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10363
msgid ""
"The size of the packetcache can be observed with <command>/etc/init.d/pdns "
"show packetcache-size</command>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><sect2><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10366
msgid "Query Cache"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><sect2><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10368
msgid ""
"Besides entire packets, PDNS can also cache individual backend queries. Each "
"DNS query leads to a number of backend queries, the most obvious additional "
"backend query is the check for a possible CNAME. So, when a query comes in "
"for the 'A' record for 'www.powerdns.com', PDNS must first check for a CNAME "
"for 'www.powerdns.com'."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><sect2><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10373
msgid ""
"The Query Cache caches these backend queries, many of which are quite "
"repetitive. PDNS only caches queries with no answer, or with exactly one. In "
"the future this may be expanded but this lightweight solution is very simple "
"and therefore fast."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><sect2><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10377
msgid ""
"Most gain is made from caching negative entries, ie, queries that have no "
"answer. As these take little memory to store and are typically not a real "
"problem in terms of speed-of-propagation, the default TTL for negative "
"queries is a rather high 60 seconds."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><sect2><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10381
msgid ""
"This only is a problem when first doing a query for a record, adding it, and "
"immediately doing a query for that record again. It may then take up to 60 "
"seconds to appear. Changes to existing records however do not fall under the "
"negative query ttl (<command>negquery-cache-ttl</command>), but under the "
"generic <command>query-cache-ttl</command> which defaults to 20 seconds."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><sect2><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10386
msgid ""
"The default values should work fine for many sites. When tuning, keep in "
"mind that the Query Cache mostly saves database access but that the Packet "
"Cache also saves a lot of CPU because 0 internal processing is done when "
"answering a question from the Packet Cache."
msgstr ""

