#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10714
msgid "A brief introduction to DNSSEC"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10716
msgid ""
"DNSSEC is a complicated subject, but it is not required to know all the ins "
"and outs of this protocol to be able to use PowerDNSSEC.  In this section, "
"we explain the core concepts that are needed to operate a PowerDNSSEC "
"installation."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10720
msgid ""
"Zone material is enhanced with signatures using 'keys'. Such a signature "
"(called an RRSIG) is a cryptographic guarantee that the data served is the "
"original data. DNSSEC keys are asymmetric (RSA, DSA or GOST), the public "
"part is published over DNS and is called a DNSKEY record, and is used for "
"verification. The private part is used for signing and is never published."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10725
msgid ""
"To make sure that the internet knows that the key that is used for signing "
"is the authentic key, confirmation can be gotten from the parent zone. This "
"means that to become operational, a zone operator will have to publish a "
"representation of the signing key to the parent zone, often a ccTLD or a "
"gTLD. This representation is called a DS record, and is a shorter (hashed) "
"version of the DNSKEY."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10730
msgid ""
"Once the parent zone has the DS, and the zone is signed with the DNSSEC key, "
"we are done in theory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10733
msgid ""
"However, for a variety of reasons, most DNSSEC operations run with another "
"layer of keys. The so called 'Key Signing Key' is sent to the parent zone, "
"and this Key Signing Key is used to sign a new set of keys called the Zone "
"Signing Keys."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10737
msgid ""
"This setup allows us to change our keys without having to tell the zone "
"operator about it."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10740
msgid ""
"A final challenge is how to DNSSEC sign the answer 'no such domain'. In the "
"language of DNS, the way to say 'there is no such domain' (NXDOMAIN)  or "
"there is no such record type is to send an empty answer. Such empty answers "
"are universal, and can't be signed."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10744
msgid ""
"In DNSSEC parlance we therefore sign a record that says 'there are no "
"domains between A.powerdnssec.org and C.powerdnssec.org'. This securely "
"tells the world that B.powerdnssec.org does not exist. This solution is "
"called NSEC, and is simple but has downsides - it also tells the world "
"exactly which records DO exist."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10749
msgid ""
"So alternatively, we can say that if a certain mathematical operation (an "
"'iterated salted hash') is performed on a question, that no valid answers "
"exist that have as outcome of this operation an answer between two very "
"large numbers. This leads to the same 'proof of non-existence'. This "
"solution is called NSEC3."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10754
msgid ""
"A PowerDNSSEC zone can either be operated in NSEC or in one of two NSEC3 "
"modes ('inclusive' and 'narrow')."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10758
msgid "Profile, Supported Algorithms, Record Types &amp; Modes of operation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:10760
msgid ""
"PowerDNSSEC aims to serve unexciting, standards compliant, DNSSEC "
"information. One goal is to have relevant parts of our output be identical "
