#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11252
msgid "Modes of operation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11254
msgid ""
"PowerDNSSEC can operate in several modes. In the simplest situation, there "
"is a single \"SQL\" database that contains, in separate tables, all domain "
"data, keying material and other DNSSEC related settings."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11258
msgid ""
"This database is then replicated to all PowerDNS instances, which all serve "
"identical records, keys and signatures."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11262
msgid ""
"In this mode of operation, care should be taken that the database "
"replication occurs over a secure network, or over an encrypted "
"connection. This is because keying material, if intercepted, could be used "
"to counterfeit DNSSEC data using the original keys."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11267
msgid ""
"Such a single replicated database requires no further attention beyond "
"monitoring already required during non-DNSSEC operations."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11270
msgid "PowerDNSSEC Pre-signed records"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11272
msgid ""
"In this mode, PowerDNS serves zones that already contain DNSSEC "
"records. Such zones can either be slaved from a remote master, or can be "
"signed using tools like OpenDNSSEC, ldns-signzone or dnssec-signzone."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11276
msgid "PowerDNSSEC Front-signing"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11278
msgid ""
"As a special feature, PowerDNSSEC can operate as a signing server which "
"operates as a slave to an unsigned master."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11282
msgid ""
"In this way, if keying material is available for an unsigned zone that is "
"retrieved from a master server, this keying material will be used when "
"serving data from this zone."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11286
msgid ""
"As part of the zone retrieval, the equivalent of 'pdnssec rectify-zone' is "
"run to make sure that all DNSSEC-related fields are set correctly."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11290
msgid "PowerDNSSEC BIND-mode operation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11292
msgid ""
"Starting with PowerDNS 3.1, the bindbackend can manage keys in an SQLite3 "
"database without launching a separate gsqlite3 backend."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11296
msgid ""
"To use this mode, add \"bind-dnssec-db=/var/db/bind-dnssec-db.sqlite3\" to "
"pdns.conf, and run \"pdnssec create-bind-db "
"/var/db/bind-dnssec-db.sqlite3\". Then, restart PowerDNS."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11300
msgid ""
"After this, you can use \"pdnssec secure-zone\" and all other pdnssec "
"commands on your BIND zones without trouble."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11304
msgid "PowerDNSSEC hybrid BIND-mode operation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><warning><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11307
msgid ""
"This mode is only supported in 3.0 and 3.0.1! In 3.1 and up, the bindbackend "
"always does its own key storage."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11312
msgid ""
"PowerDNS can also operate based on 'BIND'-style zone &amp; configuration "
"files. This 'bindbackend' has full knowledge of DNSSEC, but has no native "
"way of storing keying material."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11316
msgid ""
"However, since PowerDNS supports operation with multiple simultaneous "
"backends, this is not a problem."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11319
msgid ""
"In hybrid mode, keying material and zone records are stored in different "
"backends. This allows for 'bindbackend' operation in full DNSSEC mode."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11323
msgid ""
"To benefit from this mode, include at least one database-based backend in "
"the 'launch' statement. The Generic SQLite backend version 3 (gsqlite3) "
"probably complements BIND mode best, since it does not require a database "
"server process."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><warning><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11328
msgid ""
"For now, it is necessary to execute a manual SQL 'insert' into the domains "
"table of the backend hosting the keying material. This is needed to generate "
"a zone-id for the relevant domain. Sample SQL statement: <command>insert "
"into domains (name, type) values ('powerdnssec.org', 'NATIVE');</command>."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11335
msgid "Rules for filling out fields in database backends"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><para><note><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11337
msgid ""
"The BIND Backend automates all the steps outlined below, and does not need "
"'manual' help"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11340
msgid ""
"For DNSSEC, two additional fields are important: 'auth' and "
"'ordername'. These fields are set correctly on an incoming zone transfer, "
"and also by running 'pdnssec rectify-zone', or 'zone2sql' with the --dnssec "
"flag."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11343
msgid ""
"The 'auth' field should be set to '1' for data for which the zone itself is "
"authoritative, which includes the SOA record and its own NS records."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11347
msgid ""
"The 'auth' field should be 0 however for NS records which are used for "
"delegation, and also for any glue (A, AAAA) records present for this "
"purpose. Do note that the DS record for a secure delegation should be "
"authoritative!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11351
msgid ""
"The 'ordername' field needs to be filled out depending on the NSEC/NSEC3 "
"mode. When running in NSEC3 'Narrow' mode, the ordername field is ignored "
"and best left empty. In NSEC mode, the ordername field should be NULL for "
"any glue but filled in for delegation NS records and all authoritative "
"records. In NSEC3 opt-out mode (the only NSEC3 mode PowerDNS currently "
"supports), any non-authoritative records (as described for the 'auth' field) "
"should have ordername set to NULL."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11357
msgid ""
"In 'NSEC' mode, it should contain the <emphasis>relative</emphasis> part of "
"a domain name, in reverse order, with dots replaced by spaces. So "
"'www.uk.powerdnssec.org' in the 'powerdnssec.org' zone should have 'uk www' "
"as its ordername."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11361
msgid ""
"In 'NSEC3' non-narrow mode, the ordername should contain a lowercase "
"base32hex encoded representation of the salted &amp; iterated hash of the "
"full record name. <command>pdnssec hash-zone-record zone record</command> "
"can be used to calculate this hash."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11368
msgid ""
"During typical PowerDNSSEC operation, the private part of the signing keys "
"are 'online', which can be compared to operating an HTTPS server, where the "
"certificate is available on the webserver for cryptographic purposes."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:11372
msgid ""
"In some settings, having such (private) keying material available online is "
"considered undesirable. In this case, consider running in pre-signed mode."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><appendix><sect1><sect2><title>
