#: docs/pdns.xml:13174
msgid ""
"Consider the following simple example: <placeholder type=\"programlisting\" "
"id=\"0\"/> Upon an incoming AXFR, PowerDNS calls our `axfrfilter` function "
"for each record. All HINFO records are replaced by a TXT record with a TTL "
"of 99 seconds and the specified string. TXT Records with names starting with "
"`_tstamp.` get their value (_rdata_) set to the current time stamp.  All "
"other records are unhandled."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><appendix><sect1><sect2><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:13217 docs/pdns.xml:15596
msgid "Master operation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:13219
msgid ""
"When operating as a master, PDNS sends out notifications of changes to "
"slaves, which react to these notifications by querying PDNS to see if the "
"zone changed, and transferring its contents if it has. Notifications are a "
"way to promptly propagate zone changes to slaves, as described in RFC 1996."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para><warning><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:13226
msgid ""
"Master support is OFF by default, turn it on by adding "
"<command>master</command> to the configuration. The same holds for slave "
"operation. Both can be on simultaneously."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:13233
msgid ""
"Left open by RFC 1996 is who is to be notified - which is harder to figure "
"out than it sounds. All slaves for this domain must receive a notification "
"but the nameserver only knows the names of the slaves - not the IP "
"addresses, which is where the problem lies. The nameserver itself might be "
"authoritative for the name of its secondary, but not have the data "
"available."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:13238
msgid ""
"To resolve this issue, PDNS tries multiple tactics to figure out the IP "
"addresses of the slaves, and notifies everybody. In contrived configurations "
"this may lead to duplicate notifications being sent out, which shouldn't "
"hurt."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:13242
msgid ""
"Some backends may be able to detect zone changes, others may chose to let "
"the operator indicate which zones have changed and which haven't.  Consult "
"the documentation for your backend to see how it processes changes in zones."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:13246
msgid ""
"To help deal with slaves that may have missed notifications, or have failed "
"to respond to them, several override commands are available via the "
"pdns_control tool (<xref linkend=\"pdnscontrol\"/>):"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para><variablelist><varlistentry><term>
#: docs/pdns.xml:13252
msgid "pdns_control notify <command>domain</command>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para><variablelist><varlistentry><listitem><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:13255
msgid ""
"This instructs PDNS to notify all IP addresses it considers to be slaves of "
"this domain."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para><variablelist><varlistentry><term>
#: docs/pdns.xml:13260
msgid "pdns_control notify-host <command>domain ip-address</command>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><sect1><para><variablelist><varlistentry><listitem><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:13263
msgid ""
"This is truly an override and sends a notification to an arbitrary IP "
"address. Can be used in 'also-notify' situations or when PDNS has trouble "
"figuring out who to notify - which may happen in contrived configurations."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><title>
#: docs/pdns.xml:13272
msgid "Fancy records for seamless email and URL integration"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><para><warning><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:13276
msgid ""
"As of PowerDNS Authoritative Server 3.0, fancy records are no longer "
"supported!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:13281
msgid ""
"PDNS also supports so called 'fancy' records. A Fancy Record is actually not "
"a DNS record, but it is translated into one. Currently, two fancy records "
"are implemented, but not very useful without additional unreleased "
"software. For completeness, they are listed here.  The software will become "
"available later on and is part of the Express and PowerMail suite of "
"programs."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><para>
#: docs/pdns.xml:13286
msgid ""
"These records imply extra database lookups which has a performance "
"impact. Therefore fancy records are only queried for if they are enabled "
"with the <command>fancy-records</command> command in "
"<filename>pdns.conf</filename>."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><para><variablelist><varlistentry><term>
#: docs/pdns.xml:13292
msgid "MBOXFW"
msgstr ""

